{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-85559047cebc72f6", "type": "tool_result", "content": "# Scaling Open Discrete Audio Foundation Models with Interleaved Semantic, Acoustic, and Text Tokens\narXiv: 2602.16687\nAuthors: Potsawee Manakul, Woody Haosheng Gan, Martijn Bartelds, Guangzhi Sun, William Held, Diyi Yang\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: audio_understanding\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Systematic investigation of data sources, text mixture ratios, and token composition establishes a validated training recipe for native audio foundation models.\n  2. First scaling law study for discrete audio models via IsoFLOP analysis reveals that optimal training data grows 1.6 times faster than optimal model size.\n  3. Development of SODA, a suite of discrete audio models from 135M to 4B parameters, validating scaling predictions and demonstrating competitive performance across audio and cross-modal benchmarks.\n  4. Demonstration that SODA serves as a flexible backbone by fine-tuning for voice-preserving speech-to-speech translation using the same unified next-token prediction architecture.\n\nTags: LALM, LALM/对话型-交错标记, LALM/音频标记-融合", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "5e26e7a0-0f45-4373-822e-3119a354126e", "uuid": "d4fdbb1e-4829-4873-85ee-c7fa28ae3d9c", "timestamp": "2026-07-23T06:56:48.073Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "# Scaling Open Discrete Audio Foundation Models with Interleaved Semantic, Acoustic, and Text Tokens\narXiv: 2602.16687\nAuthors: Potsawee Manakul, Woody Haosheng Gan, Martijn Bartelds, Guangzhi Sun, William Held, Diyi Yang\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: audio_understanding\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Systematic investigation of data sources, text mixture ratios, and token composition establishes a validated training recipe for native audio foundation models.\n  2. First scaling law study for discrete audio models via IsoFLOP analysis reveals that optimal training data grows 1.6 times faster than optimal model size.\n  3. Development of SODA, a suite of discrete audio models from 135M to 4B parameters, validating scaling predictions and demonstrating competitive performance across audio and cross-modal benchmarks.\n  4. Demonstration that SODA serves as a flexible backbone by fine-tuning for voice-preserving speech-to-speech translation using the same unified next-token prediction architecture.\n\nTags: LALM, LALM/对话型-交错标记, LALM/音频标记-融合", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
